song.embed_content: Read “King” by Lauren Aquilina on Genius
song.title: King

annotations: You’re alone, you’re on your own, so what?
She might mean that it doesn’t matter if your alone, because if anything, you have what you need. You just have to recognize it

Put all your faults to bed
 You can be king again

there are traces of stoic philosophy in her message, namely the idea of understanding your faults (& obstacles) -especially the ones outside of your control- and DOing your best despite them instead of WORRYing about them (which would directly hinder you)

You’re in control
 Rid of the monsters inside your head
 Put all your faults to bed
 You can be king again
She is saying to regain your life and be okay with your flaws, and stop being self deprecating only then you will be happy.

There’s method in my madness
 There’s no logic in your sadness
He’s saying that theres no reason for her to be sad because it doesn’t make any sense.
You’re too wrapped up in your self-doubt
People tend to look at themselves and believe they are not good enough. A study showed that even 3 and 4 year old thought badly of them selves

You can reclaim your crown
 You’re in control

Once you come to accept your flaws and yourself for who you are, only then will you finally be in control of yourself and your thoughts. You would finally be the ruler of yourself instead letting others or you own self-doubt trample you.
You’ve got that young blood, set it free
She is trying to encourage this person to be themselves, that they have what it takes to be a good person.
Take it from me

Lauren suffers with anxiety and depression and in an interview with Independent, she explained how it has impacted her life and her career.

I started experiencing anxiety properly when I was about 17 and since then it comes and goes in waves. [… panic attacks] can be triggered by a multitude of things – from nightmares about a significant previous trauma in my life to less predictable causes such as getting ready to go out with my friends for the evening.

Here, she tells the listener that she knows what it’s like to be struggling with mental health but promises that they “won’t gain a single thing "from misery.”

Glass half empty, glass half full
 Well, either way, you won’t be going thirsty
 Count your blessings, not your flaws

This could mean ‘Look on the bright side’ as they say the lines “Glass half empty, glass half full” and “Count your blessings, not your flaws.”
“Glass half empty, glass half full” could be referring to how people tend to naturally look on the negative. There was a scientific study showing a glass filled halfway with water. There were two groups, A and B, and to group A, they said, “Would you like to drink this Half-full glass?” which then more people agreed to drink it than group B where the scientists said “Would you like to drink this Half-empty glass?” where more people declined. People in group B heard how the glass is half EMPTY. Empty is usually referred to as worst than ‘Full’ so they instantly said no due to how their was a negative aspect to it.
     “Count your blessings, not your flaws.” could be referring to insecurities and is saying, “Stop putting yourself down and stop looking at the bad parts of you, look at your talents and blessings!” This is as if she (Lauren Aquilina) is say, “Hey, it’s okay if you do something wrong! We’re all human, it’s what we do best! As long as we look at what makes us proud and happy and give it our attention then we will be able to get through life with a strong will and a happy heart/soul!” or A.K.A cheering her friend/close one/audience on!

Thanks for reading this!                   -Thycaus
You lost your mind in the sound

Here, “sound” could be referring to the listeners own thoughts and self doubt. However, it could also be referring to the sound of others saying their mind is so caught up in what others say, they can no longer listen to their own thoughts.

song.title: Sinners

annotations: And if we’re sinners then it feels like heaven to me

The use of “sinners” again suggests that the perspective writer acknowledges that other people may not approve of this relationship, yet by saying that this “Sin” feels like “Heaven” then they don’t care what other people say, as long as they’re happy.
But my world is only you
This is the writers way of saying that even though “the world may disapprove” but that doesn’t matter to them because their only world is their significant other.
The world may disapprove

Following the line in verse one “and judgement taught us that our hearts were wrong,” this lyrics also suggests that other people may not approve of this relationship that the perspective writer is having, but there is a chance that people may not disapprove with the use of “may”
So let’s be sinners to be saints

Being gay, according to religion, is a sin, therefore making homosexuals, sinners, however, keeping in line with the religious feeling there, Lauren (or the person the song is coming from), they say that it’s a saint, suggesting they’re leading something, or a group. The LGBTQ+ community is a group and we all have our idols.
And judgement taught us that our hearts were wrong

This lyrics could be suggesting that from a young child you are only ever taught about heterosexuality. This could explain why “out hearts are wrong”, this line suggests the world implies that whoever the perspective of the song is about, is “wrong” about who they love, which they’re not.

~ She confirmed that in an old Facebook post

And how can you expect me not to eat
 When the forbidden fruit tastes so sweet?

The story of the forbidden fruit originates back to the biblical story of Adam and Eve, the first sinners, who were tempted into eating fruit from the tree of the knowledge of good and evil in the Garden of Eden, which they had been commanded not to do by God.

Forbidden fruit is a metaphor that describes any object of desire (especially sexual) whose appeal results from the knowledge that it should not be obtained.

description.plain:
“Fools” is a song by singer Lauren Aquilina. The single is included in her Fools EP, along with three other songs.

This song is about two people who are good friends, they find themselves wanting more and this person is expressing her fear that if they jump into something, it could ruin their friendship. “I don’t want you to go, but I want you so”. She means that she is afraid of screwing it up and losing him if it doesn’t work out, but it’s too hard to deny her feelings for him and pretend to just be friends.

description.plain:
“Psycho” marks the return of pop singer & songwriter, Lauren Aquilina, after a two year break. It’s the lead single off a forthcoming EP that Aquilina plans to release in early 2019.

Lyrically, the song is a playful rebuttal to an ex-lover’s comments that the singer is “psycho” in which the singer leans into these psychotic tendencies by visiting the ex’s home in the middle of the night, climbing up the walls, stalking his newest girlfriend, and keeping a list of the other girls he messes with.

annotations: When you’re by yourself, you’re not alone

She’s constantly watching his every move, reinforcing this idea of herself being a pyscho. She plays into the label and exaggerates her actions. The fact she makes herself sound so obsessive and controlling when in reality she’s perfectly sane and her reasons to be mad and upset are justified.
Walking tragedy dressed up like the girls you dream of, dream of
She’s deliberately messing with his head.
I’m climbing up the walls
A representation of her anger as she realises that he’s been cheating on her.
Your new favorite thing
The way Aquilina sings “new favorite thing” is almost sarcastic and barbing: this conveys an idea of her ex treating girls like things, new toys rather than people.
And God can’t help you now

Both the first and second verse of the song end in almost the same way. However, in the second verse the pronoun has been changed from “me” to “you”. This could suggest that Lauren has passed the blame of the ending of the relationship from herself to her ex.

The ambiguity of the line also leaves us wondering what threat her ex is facing. It may be the “karma” that is mentioned in the previous line, as her ex’s actions come back to bite him. But it may be Lauren herself, as she becomes the irrational, aggressive, stalker-ish “psycho” she was accused of being.

I’ll add her to the list of the girls you’re fuckin’ with now
 But karma comes around

Lauren suggested in an interview that her ex may have cheated on her. This may be why she is so fixated on the idea of karma.

Maybe three weeks [after I split up with him] he already had a new girlfriend [which is] suspiciously quick.

Midnight, after dark, Jack and Coke and pour my heart out, heart out
 Oh so suddenly I’m on the front steps of your house, your house
 Hey, how’d I get here?
 It’s out of my control,

This part of the song was inspired by Lauren’s personal experience as she explained in a Q&A on twitter:

I literally went to my ex’s house in the middle of the night and sat on his front steps crying until he came out and found me. But [also] imagining what I might have ended up doing if I hadn’t got the heartbreak under control.

Jack refers to Jack Daniel’s whiskey, mixed with Coca-Cola to make a Jack and Coke. Coke may also refer to cocaine. She’s drowning her sorrow through substance abuse.

Maybe I’m a psycho just like you said I was
 You got me right, but baby it’s not my fault
 Oh and I know and I know and I know that I been acting so strange
 But you should know that you’re the one who made me this way

The singer is so smitten by her ex and outraged by the break-up that she takes every word to heart, including his accusations that she is “psycho”. Instead of turning away from the criticism, she plays into it and frames the whole song around her being exactly what he says she is.

Comparisons in the chorus can be made to Taylor Swift, whom Aquilina opened for during Taylor’s 1989 tour  . Parallels can be found to Swift’s “Blank Space” in which she leans into the media-crafted image of the artists as a maneater:

Got a long list of ex-lovers
They’ll tell you I’m insane
But I’ve got a blank space, baby
And I’ll write your name

And “Look What You Made Me Do”, which pins the artist’s unsavory actions on a man in her life that forced her hand:

Ooh, look what you made me do
Look what you made me do

description.plain:
Wonder is the fourth track on Lauren Aquilina’s debut extended play Fools. Aquilina commented in an interview with Fortitude Magazine that it was her favorite song on the EP:

‘Wonder’ was the most personal song on the EP, and we recorded it live in one take so the whole thing was very raw and natural which was lovely.
